The last time I successfully completed one of these on time was in college I think... since then I've done some throughout the year and I've fallen off the wagon, but this time I'm really committed and disciplined.

"Move" is a really loaded term for me right now. I had plans to move--to relocate--to live closer to a romantic partner, but now that's not a thing. 2022 is the year I've decided to unlearn things, and for me, "move" is one of those terms. It's not only about uprooting and relocating to a physical location. Moving can be the intentional effort of being present and aware and in tune with my body and my needs and not neglecting myself anymore to pursue what I think everyone else wants me to be.

So MOVE in this context is to return to center and to unlearn the concept that I am a product of everything else around me. No. I am myself and myself might be comprised of the universe but I am not solely what everyone else defines me to be or needs me to be. I need to define myself. I need to show up for myself. I need to grow for myself. I need to be in touch with myself for my own benefit. Moving is my control of my body because of my will. And my will and my needs and my desires and all that I am are important and not to be lost to the world.

This will rock my foundation and my world view but it is the challenge I think is necessary and I am prepared to embark on.

So I did 30 days of daily yoga in January 2021â€¦and then I kept going. I wanted to be able to sit on the floor with my students. I wanted to be able to move with less aches and pains. I followed Adriene's monthly practice calendar for the past 365 days. Every day. I really resonate with the principals encouraged in the practices:
Bring the breath.
Showing up on the mat is the hardest part.
Find what feels good for your body.
Take what you need and leave what you donâ€™t.
Things Iâ€™ve gained: 
1. Carved out time for myself every single day. Even if it was only a 7 min bedtime practice, I got on the mat every day.
2. I suck at time management and many of my practices happened at 11 pm or later. Gotta work on this for the coming year.
3. I can sit on the floor, cross legged, with my students and get up without help! This was really the goal all along. I just wanted to be able to do my job better which included getting to the floor with my students.
4. Extended childâ€™s pose is amazingâ€¦but Iâ€™ve also found myself in tears many times in this position of total surrender.
5. Yoga is emotional. Iâ€™ve cried many, many times as emotions get released from the craziest places like your hips! Who knew?!
6. I never thought I would consider Down Dog as a position of rest but it can be. Again, who knew?
7. In times of stress and time crunch, some days, all I could manage was a bedtime routine or a 10 min stretch routine. I tried to give myself grace on those days (and there were many) and be happy that I made it to the mat.
8. I find that my body actually craves the daily stretch and flow of yoga now which is mind boggling to me.
9. Practice really does make things better. Not perfect. Better.
10. I like consistency and found this yoga practice design to be spot on for consistency. Some days, the daily practice dialed in on exactly what I needed and for the length of time that I could handle. Not sure how they knew that! And it provided just the right amount of challenge for me so that I looked forward to practicing most days and didnâ€™t feel defeated.
11. I have a long way to go and much more flexibility to gain physically, mentally, emotionally and spiritually.
12. I talk to God a lot during my practice. For me, God is my higher power and acknowledging and being grateful for this amazing life I get to live on a daily basis with a body that is a work in progress was a gift. Take the time. You wonâ€™t regret it. I'm ready to flow into 2022 with a steady practice as my anchor. Thank you, Adriene and community, for being with me every single day of 2021.

Your videos have been one of the few things keeping me sane the last few months while dealing with some health issues. There were moments I felt so weak I thought even the most basic poses might break me, and as a young and otherwise in shape person that was scary. I wanted to give up, but I didn't. I took a step back, went back to the basics, and focused on my breath. I explored these poses with a new sense of curiosity and discovered strength, that after years of yoga, I didn't know I had. So, my resolution this year is to stay curious. Every time I think I have things figured out when it comes to my body, I realize there is something new to discover. The illness didn't go away, but I feel stronger now than I did before the diagnosis. Thank you for that. P.S. Everyone should be doing Day 16 of Breath daily. The real game changer.
